{"cursor":"3985","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = name = Franz Roubaud honorific_suffix = image = caption =\n| birth_name = Franz Alekseyevich Roubaud birth_date = birth_place = Odessa,\n| Ukraine death_date = death_place = Munich, Germany death_cause = nationality =\n| Russian citizenship = education = alma_mater = occupation = years_active =\n| known_for = notable_works = panoramic painting style = influences = influenced\n| = home_town = title = term = spouse = partner = children = parents = relatives\n| = awards = signature = signature_alt = signature_size = website = \n| footnotes = box_width =\n}}\n\n'Franz Alekseyevich Roubaud' was a Russian Empire painter who created some of\nthe largest and best known panoramic paintings.\n\nRoubaud was born on 15 June 1856 in Odessa, now Ukraine and attended art school\nthere. In 1877, he went to Munich and studied at the Munich Academy. He then\nsettled in Saint Petersburg, working in the Imperial Academy of Arts and\npainting huge panoramas of historical battles. During this time he painted:\n* Russo-Persian War (1804â1813) - unveiled 1892\n* Storm of Achulgo â unveiled 1896, Tiflis, now under restoration in museum of\n  graphic arts in Makhachkala, Daghestan\n* Siege of Sevastopol (1854) â unveiled in 1905, damaged during the Siege of\n  Sevastopol (1942), restored 1950s\n* Battle of Borodino (1812) â unveiled 1911, moved to Poklonnaya Hill in\n  Moscow in 1962\n\nRoubaud's works were so large that they required pavilions specially built to\nexhibit them.\n\nIn 1913, Roubaud left Russia for Munich, where he died on 13 March 1928.\n","linknr":147,"url":"Franz_Roubaud","recorded":1371245429,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Franz_Roubaud&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Franz_Roubaud&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php